<p>
  Within this context stands <strong>Joshua Wiley Jones</strong>, my fifth great-grandfather.
  Through him, the Jones family became part of the human fabric that surrounded the Biltmore
  enterprise during its formative era. Joshua Wiley Jones passed his line through his son,
  <strong>Jackson Jones</strong>, who in turn became the father of <strong>Sally Jones</strong>.
</p>

<p>
  Sally Jones married <strong>Oscar Archibald Rogers</strong>, a union that joined the Jones and
  Rogers families and carried this branch of the family forward. This marriage marks the point
  at which the Jones lineage merges directly into the Rogers line within my own ancestry,
  creating a documented bridge between two western North Carolina families.
</p>

<p>
  During the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, the Biltmore Estate functioned as
  far more than a single household. Its construction, forestry operations, farms, road systems,
  and service infrastructure required the labor and skills of families from nearby towns and
  rural areas. Families such as the Jones and Rogers were part of the regional workforce and
  community that supported this vast enterprise, often forming multigenerational ties to the
  land.
</p>

